M&S kitted out to fight new wave of rivals
Marks & Spencer chief Marc Bolland tells Graham Ruddick how he plans to transform the high street business into an "international multi–channel" retailer.
Marks & Spencer this year enlisted model and actress Rosie Huntington-Whiteley to design a lingerie collection. Photo: MARKS & SPENCER	By Graham Ruddick, Retail Correspondent
7:11AM GMT 07 Nov 2012
Comments
With Marks & Spencer profits down 10pc and like–for–like clothing sales 4.3pc lower, is this a sign that the retailer's once–dominant grip on the British clothing market is well and truly over? Britain may have spent most of 2012 in recession but, on the same day M&S reported a sharp decline, Primark said its sales rose 15pc. Primark's annual revenues have now cleared £3.5bn for the first time, more than double what they were five years ago. The rise of Primark and its low–cost clothing illustrates the changing face of British high streets and the fierce competition M&S faces, particularly in womenswear. Walk down Oxford Street in London and challengers to M&S are everywhere, from traditional rivals such as Next, Debenhams and John Lewis, to the strengthening cheap and cheerful competitors such as Primark and the foreign retailers which have arrived over the past decade, such as H&M, Uniqlo and the impressive Zara, financed by Inditex, the biggest clothing retailer in the world. Consumers now have more options than ever, and they are not afraid to take them. In the face of such competition and global economic uncertainty, M&S clothing – particularly in womenswear – has left consumers underwhelmed and often bemoaning its quality. Related Articles
