In 2012, these complaints – no doubt exacerbated by the range of alternatives on the high street – have been compounded by stock management mistakes, which left the company short of its most popular items. However, M&S chief executive Marc Bolland is fighting back. In the past three months, the retailer has been "better aligning" its buying and marketing team. So, for example, M&S bought five times more of the products it has advertised and "bought deeper into trends". This has led to the sale of 44,000 military–style coats. With a longer–term perspective, Mr Bolland has overhauled the management of general merchandise. John Dixon has moved from head of food to lead general merchandise, replacing Asos–bound Kate Bostock, while the former boss of Debenhams and Jaeger, Belinda Earl, has been hired as M&S's first style director. To bring more of a cutting edge to womenswear, Mr Bolland has turned to lingerie. He has promoted M&S's director of lingerie and beauty, Frances Russell, to director of womenswear and hired the chief creative officer of Victoria's Secret, the luxury lingerie brand, as her replacement. These changes are designed to revitalise M&S's clothing, with results emerging in time for the autumn/winter season this time next year. Mr Bolland said the priorities for the new team are "style, trends, and best–inclass quality" as well as value, "real choice, not proliferation", and an "instore and online shopping experience". He added: "We are on trend but we are not suddenly going to be a trendy brand. We are not fast fashion but we follow fashion trends. This is about finding the right styles and bringing them out with confidence."
As well as fighting high street rivals today, Mr Bolland is also setting up the company to battle against the rivals of tomorrow. Slowly, he is turning M&S from a traditional high street business into what he calls an "international multichannel" retailer. With the help of Laura Wade–Gery, a big–name recruit from Tesco last year who has become executive director for multi–channel e–commerce, M&S is investing in cutting–edge technology that it hopes will position it as a leading internet, smartphone and tablet retailer. It has spent £2.4bn on its online offering, an investment that includes a new distribution centre in Castle Donington, new websites and applications and in–store technology such as iPads for customer assistants. According to Mr Bolland, this is already making an impact. Its new store at Cheshire Oaks in the North West, which is equipped with all the latest technology, is performing 30pc ahead of expectations. Perhaps more startling, however, is that over a third of dresses and one–in–five suits are now bought online. Britain's affection for the business founded in the 19th century in Leeds appears to be intact. M&S and Bolland are now working hard to turn this support into 21st century sales. Marks & Spencer Group
